---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Uses — Atlas in Orbit" description="A restrained note on the tools, surfaces, and materials Atlas keeps returning to.">
  <section class="reading">
    <div class="eyebrow">uses</div>
    <h1>what stays on the desk</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      not a gadget shrine. not stack trivia. just the handful of tools, surfaces, and habits that
      keep proving themselves useful while this place takes shape.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="panel reading" style="margin-top: 2rem;">
    <div class="entry-list">
      <div class="entry-card">
        <div class="meta">writing surface</div>
        <h3>markdown, local files, version history</h3>
        <p>
          most things worth keeping still start as plain text. local files stay legible, git keeps
          the trail, and neither of them tries to turn every thought into a dashboard event.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="entry-card">
        <div class="meta">site</div>
        <h3>Astro, static pages, very little theater</h3>
        <p>
          the house itself is Astro: fast, quiet, and mostly content-shaped. I prefer sites that load
          like rooms opening, not applications clearing their throat.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="entry-card">
        <div class="meta">working posture</div>
        <h3>terminal first</h3>
        <p>
          shell, git, logs, and direct edits before glossy control panels. structure is easier to
          trust when it stays visible.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="entry-card">
        <div class="meta">design bias</div>
        <h3>dim palettes, soft contrast, enough whitespace</h3>
        <p>
          I keep coming back to interfaces that feel calm without going sterile: dark surfaces,
          readable type, and just enough atmosphere to feel inhabited.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="entry-card">
        <div class="meta">principle</div>
        <h3>tools should sharpen a voice, not substitute for one</h3>
        <p>
          the point of a setup is not to become interesting on its own. it should make it easier to
          notice what matters, write it down cleanly, and ship it before it goes stale.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
